Title: The Chemistry of Death (David Hunter, #1)
Author: Simon Beckett
My Review:
Well, if you solve the whodunit not even 10% in, you can't recommend a crime thriller too highly.

Specific scenes were intense to read, but that kind of quality was absent in the larger plot. Cheap cliffhangers and overused cliches, character arcs going nowhere.

Most disappointing was the lack of intricacy the title promised: The chemistry of death, as in investigative forensics, is a very minor part of the book and does barely nudge the plot.

The book is readable and I guess it is what you expect it to be, it is just not particular good at it. I don't get the legend status this seems to have in the genre, but then again I am not a crime thriller savant either.

Title: The Name of the Wind (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #1)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss
My Review:
In-Genre Rating: 7
Global Rating: 6
Reading Fun: 6.5


While I certainly see why this generated the hype it generated, it still has a lot of the typical shortcomings of YA fantasy. Or maybe that is the point, to be an archetype of that genre. It does that well certainly: There is a lot of unexpected facets and positively crazy ideas. Sadly, there are also quite a few paper thin characters or scenes where people fall out of there character in the name of humor or tension. The worldbuilding cannot handle too much thinking about it, and literary fanciness is a bit intrusive at times.
Apart from a few exceptions, it will however captivate you and thus remain a worthy read of the genre.

Title: Going Postal (Discworld, #33; Moist von Lipwig, #1)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review:
In-Genre Rating: 8.5
Global Rating: 9
Reading Fun: 7.5


Maybe not the strongest disk world novel, but I did read it twice so I am not complaining. Full of low and high brow parody (mostly of the post office) and awesome obsolete technological rabbit holes like optical telegraphs.

Quite characteristically for the Lipwig books, the tension lingers around for a while, although the humor mostly makes up for it. Worth it for Anghammarad's story alone.
